<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1059,1462,1572]" pageId="6" pageNumber="965">
D i a g n o s i s: The genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kirsch" authorityYear="1871" box="[468,594,1462,1483]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Aphelocerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="966" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[468,594,1462,1483]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="965">Aphelocerus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
KIRSCH was revised in 2005 (OPITZ 2005). This work included a key to species. The available 
<taxonomicName box="[679,861,1491,1513]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Aphelocerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="965" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tigra">
<emphasis box="[679,861,1491,1513]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="965">Aphelocerus tigra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimens key out to 
<emphasis box="[178,287,1521,1542]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="965">A. capillus</emphasis>
OPITZ from which 
<taxonomicName box="[488,567,1521,1542]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Aphelocerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="965" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tigra">
<emphasis box="[488,567,1521,1542]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="965">A. tigra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimens differ by showing a narrower elytral anterior white setal patch, and the elytral subapex shows more white setae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1059,211,497]" pageId="7" pageNumber="966">
D e s c r i p t i o n: Size: Length 5.0 mm; width 2.0 mm. Form: As in 
<figureCitation box="[895,980,211,233]" captionStart="Figs 266-269" captionStartId="94.[151,191,1506,1528]" captionTargetBox="[152,1060,216,1486]" captionTargetId="figure@94.[152,1060,196,1490]" captionTargetPageId="94" captionText="Figs 266-269: Habitus; (266) Aphelocerus nolus; (267) A. sparicapillus; (268) A. tigra; (269) A. yaguare." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746794" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746794/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="966">Fig. 268</figureCitation>
. Color: Black; row of white setae on basal region of elytral sutural margin, these setae not contiguous with anterior white setal patch, elytral disc with two well- developed white setal patches. Head: Interocular depression and frontal umbo shallow; antenna (
<figureCitation box="[987,1050,299,321]" captionStart="Figs 1-27" captionStartId="70.[151,191,1302,1324]" captionTargetBox="[155,1057,207,1268]" captionTargetId="figure@70.[155,1058,207,1283]" captionTargetPageId="70" captionText="Figs 1-27: Antennae; (1) Aphelocerus nodus; (2) A. copanus; (3) A. magnipannus; (4) A. yoro; (5) A. sparicapillus; (6) A. tigra. (7) A. nolus; (8) A. ligulus; (9) Perilypus schusteri; (10) P. apunctus; (11) P. virgulatus; (12) P. izabal; (13) P. alpinus; (14) Cregya fuscomacula; (15) Phonius versus; (16) Pujoliclerus ariquemes; (17) Pelonium falcatum; (18) Pujoliclerus cnecostus; (19) P. trunculus. (20) P. sentus; (21) P. testudinatus; (22) P. catie; (23) P. flavidus; (24) P. convexus; (25) P. meloinus; (26) P. mexicoensis; (27) P. tuxtlas." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746746" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746746/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="966">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
) capitate, funicular antennomeres filiform, progressively shorter and wider towards capitulum, capitulum compact; eyes finely facetted, eye narrower than frons (EW/FW 15/45). Thorax: Pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[445,536,387,409]" captionStart="Figs 101-117" captionStartId="75.[151,191,1477,1499]" captionTargetBox="[152,1030,198,1448]" captionTargetId="figure@75.[152,1030,198,1465]" captionTargetPageId="75" captionText="Figs 101-117: Pronota; (101) Aphelocerus ligulus; (102) A. yoro; (103) Ridica achira; (104) R. merida; (105) Ampleris cacuminis; (106) Plocamocera catalexis; (107) Aphelocerus tigra; (108) A. sparicapillus; (109) A. nolus; (110) A. magnipannus; (111) Pyticeroides desodes; (112) Cregya petalosa; (113) C. livida; (114) C. tobagoensis; (115) C. maura; (116) Pujoliclerus flavidus; (117) Amboakis collucoatis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746756" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746756/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="966">Fig. 107</figureCitation>
) quadrate, very finely punctate; (PW/PL 82/82); elytral disc with well-developed anterior and posterior white setal patches, disc with striae of very small setiferous punctures (EL/EW 230/60). Abdomen: Pygidium transverse 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[254,261,475,497]" pageId="7" pageNumber="966">/</emphasis>
scutiform; aedeagus as in 
<figureCitation box="[530,622,475,497]" captionStart="Figs 207-212" captionStartId="84.[151,191,1256,1278]" captionTargetBox="[153,1061,199,1242]" captionTargetId="figure@84.[153,1061,199,1242]" captionTargetPageId="84" captionText="Figs 207-212: Aedeagi; (207) Aphelocerus tigra; (208) A. yoro; (209) Perilypus alpinus; (210) P. apunctus; (211) P. arsus; (212) P. izabal." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746774" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746774/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="966">Fig. 207.</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
